1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:01,720
- Thanks to Brilliant for sponsoring this video

2
00:00:01,889 --> 00:00:02,999
and supporting my channel.

3
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:05,870
Take a second to imagine an alternate version of your life,

4
00:00:05,870 --> 00:00:08,099
one where you always knew the right choice to make

5
00:00:08,099 --> 00:00:09,296
given any decision.

6
00:00:09,297 --> 00:00:10,359
And this version of your life

7
00:00:10,359 --> 00:00:11,439
would be pretty awesome, right?

8
00:00:11,439 --> 00:00:13,279
Not only would you always make the right choice,

9
00:00:13,279 --> 00:00:14,359
which would mean that you're probably

10
00:00:14,359 --> 00:00:15,379
a billionaire at this point,

11
00:00:15,380 --> 00:00:17,549
but you also wouldn't spend a whole lot of time

12
00:00:17,550 --> 00:00:19,400
deliberating over your choices.

13
00:00:19,399 --> 00:00:21,919
You would always see the right one and instantly pick it.

14
00:00:21,920 --> 00:00:24,210
Now, provided that you are not Dr. Strange,

15
00:00:24,210 --> 00:00:26,150
that you can't simply look forward into the future

16
00:00:26,149 --> 00:00:27,699
and see which path you should take,

17
00:00:27,699 --> 00:00:29,229
you're probably like the rest of us.

18
00:00:29,230 --> 00:00:30,930
You don't always know the best decision to make,

19
00:00:30,929 --> 00:00:32,699
and if you're anything like me,

20
00:00:32,700 --> 00:00:34,640
that means you overthink your decisions

21
00:00:34,640 --> 00:00:35,930
more often than you would like.

22
00:00:35,929 --> 00:00:37,969
You get caught up in analysis paralysis,

23
00:00:37,969 --> 00:00:40,178
and that's the problem that I wanna tackle in this video

24
00:00:40,179 --> 00:00:43,259
because overthinking can be a huge detriment to our lives.

25
00:00:43,259 --> 00:00:45,299
It can cause us to procrastinate more than we want,

26
00:00:45,299 --> 00:00:47,779
it can cause us to completely set decisions aside

27
00:00:47,780 --> 00:00:48,999
because they're too stressful.

28
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:51,319
And most importantly, it can cause us to miss out

29
00:00:51,320 --> 00:00:53,110
on fleeting windows of opportunity

30
00:00:53,109 --> 00:00:54,409
that don't stay open forever.

31
00:00:54,409 --> 00:00:56,768
In our pursuit of finding the best option,

32
00:00:56,770 --> 00:00:58,530
we often lose out on that best option

33
00:00:58,530 --> 00:00:59,989
because we hesitate too much.

34
00:00:59,990 --> 00:01:01,669
And as I see it, overthinking is actually

35
00:01:01,670 --> 00:01:03,980
underpinned by a few more fundamental problems

36
00:01:03,979 --> 00:01:05,358
related to decision-making.

37
00:01:05,359 --> 00:01:08,408
Three of the biggest are fear in the decision making process

38
00:01:08,409 --> 00:01:10,949
and abundance of choice which can paralyze us.

39
00:01:10,950 --> 00:01:13,300
And a lack of proper prioritization,

40
00:01:13,299 --> 00:01:15,198
which doesn't give us clear direction.

41
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:17,450
So, what I wanna do in this video is share some strategies,

42
00:01:17,450 --> 00:01:19,559
and mindset shifts, and mental tactics

43
00:01:19,560 --> 00:01:22,910
that you can use to maybe not fix these problems entirely,

44
00:01:22,909 --> 00:01:25,619
but reduce their influence in your life.

45
00:01:25,620 --> 00:01:27,829
And the first one that I wanna talk about is a mindset shift

46
00:01:27,829 --> 00:01:30,279
that I think is the most important one you can make

47
00:01:30,280 --> 00:01:32,220
for becoming more comfortable making decisions

48
00:01:32,219 --> 00:01:33,909
and being able to make them more quickly,

49
00:01:33,909 --> 00:01:35,019
and more confidently.

50
00:01:35,019 --> 00:01:36,639
And that is making a mental shift

51
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:38,680
from what I call the set-path outlook

52
00:01:38,680 --> 00:01:40,700
to the experimental outlook.

53
00:01:40,700 --> 00:01:42,010
The set-path outlook is the thought

54
00:01:42,010 --> 00:01:43,820
that whatever decision you make right now

55
00:01:43,819 --> 00:01:46,799
is going to lock you onto a path for the rest of your life.

56
00:01:46,799 --> 00:01:48,789
It's kinda like choosing to get on a roller coaster,

57
00:01:48,790 --> 00:01:50,419
you make the choice to sit in the seat,

58
00:01:50,420 --> 00:01:51,920
you bring the bar down at ratchets,

59
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:54,210
sticks you in the seat, and then you're on a track.

60
00:01:54,209 --> 00:01:55,169
It's gonna take you somewhere

61
00:01:55,170 --> 00:01:58,089
you cannot deviate from the set-path,

62
00:01:58,090 --> 00:02:01,690
but most of the decisions we make in life are not like that.

63
00:02:01,689 --> 00:02:02,739
There are a few, yes.

64
00:02:02,739 --> 00:02:05,339
If you are standing at the very edge of the Grand Canyon,

65
00:02:05,340 --> 00:02:07,569
then the cardinal direction of your very next step

66
00:02:07,569 --> 00:02:09,638
has the potential to be pretty life altering.

67
00:02:09,639 --> 00:02:10,929
But for the most part,

68
00:02:10,930 --> 00:02:12,809
the decisions we make in our lives,

69
00:02:12,810 --> 00:02:16,200
don't set us upon a completely fixed set-path.

70
00:02:16,199 --> 00:02:17,999
We have the ability to pivot

71
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:19,770
and to iterate upon our decisions

72
00:02:19,770 --> 00:02:21,610
at the next junction point.

73
00:02:21,610 --> 00:02:23,900
That's the crux of the experimental outlook,

74
00:02:23,900 --> 00:02:27,190
viewing decisions as experiments, being like a scientist,

75
00:02:27,189 --> 00:02:28,489
realizing the choices we make

76
00:02:28,490 --> 00:02:29,970
are going to get us consequences

77
00:02:29,969 --> 00:02:32,228
or rewards in the short term, maybe both.

78
00:02:32,229 --> 00:02:33,929
They're also going to get us data,

79
00:02:33,930 --> 00:02:35,079
They're gonna get us information

80
00:02:35,080 --> 00:02:36,880
that we could not have gotten otherwise,

81
00:02:36,879 --> 00:02:39,488
which will allow us to pivot and go onto a new path

82
00:02:39,490 --> 00:02:41,659
if we don't like the one that we see ourselves on.

83
00:02:41,659 --> 00:02:43,519
And this applies not only to small choices,

84
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:44,919
but also to big ones,

85
00:02:44,919 --> 00:02:47,139
ones that feel monumental in the moment.

86
00:02:47,139 --> 00:02:48,749
I remember when I was a freshman in college,

87
00:02:48,750 --> 00:02:50,129
I thought my choice of major

88
00:02:50,129 --> 00:02:51,588
was gonna set me on a path for life,

89
00:02:51,590 --> 00:02:54,179
and I felt that I had to pick the right one the first time,

90
00:02:54,180 --> 00:02:56,050
otherwise I would screw up my entire life.

91
00:02:56,050 --> 00:02:58,199
Well, the major I picked, MIS,

92
00:02:58,199 --> 00:03:00,478
was really intended to get me into a corporate job,

93
00:03:00,479 --> 00:03:01,698
running their computer networks

94
00:03:01,699 --> 00:03:03,859
and now I'm making YouTube videos.

95
00:03:03,860 --> 00:03:06,179
And data even shows that a third,

96
00:03:06,180 --> 00:03:09,229
a full third of college students change their major

97
00:03:09,229 --> 00:03:11,059
within the first three years of enrolling.

98
00:03:11,060 --> 00:03:13,770
I didn't change my major, but I still pivoted nonetheless.

99
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:15,699
So, if something that monumental could be pivoted

100
00:03:15,699 --> 00:03:16,809
and iterated upon,

101
00:03:16,810 --> 00:03:18,439
most of the decisions that you are faced with

102
00:03:18,439 --> 00:03:20,889
on a day-to-day basis can be as well.

103
00:03:20,889 --> 00:03:21,979
To go back to our analogy,

104
00:03:21,979 --> 00:03:24,449
most decisions are not like getting on a rollercoaster

105
00:03:24,449 --> 00:03:25,379
with a set track,

106
00:03:25,379 --> 00:03:27,519
but more like getting onto a ski slope.

107
00:03:27,520 --> 00:03:29,290
Yes, once you have picked her out to go down,

108
00:03:29,289 --> 00:03:30,569
gravity makes it pretty tough

109
00:03:30,569 --> 00:03:32,409
to crawl back to the starting point.

110
00:03:32,409 --> 00:03:34,788
But as you're going down you have agency.

111
00:03:34,789 --> 00:03:37,059
You have the ability to turn, and pivot,

112
00:03:37,060 --> 00:03:39,260
and choose where you're going to end up

113
00:03:39,259 --> 00:03:41,658
making small adjustments in the middle.

114
00:03:41,659 --> 00:03:43,298
But, how do you adopt this mindset

115
00:03:43,300 --> 00:03:44,529
into your life in the first place?

116
00:03:44,530 --> 00:03:46,040
How do you get comfortable with it?

117
00:03:46,039 --> 00:03:48,869
Because it's not like an on/off switch in your head, right?

118
00:03:48,870 --> 00:03:51,200
One of the first steps is becoming comfortable with the fact

119
00:03:51,199 --> 00:03:53,029
that almost every decision in your life

120
00:03:53,030 --> 00:03:55,380
involves incomplete information.

121
00:03:55,379 --> 00:03:57,395
Or to put it as Annie Duke does in her book,

122
00:03:57,396 --> 00:03:58,416
"Thinking in Bets."

123
00:03:58,417 --> 00:04:02,260
"Life is more like poker than it is like chess."

124
00:04:02,259 --> 00:04:03,092
See, in chess,

125
00:04:03,092 --> 00:04:05,119
you almost have perfect information when you're playing,

126
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:06,970
you can see every possible move on the board

127
00:04:06,969 --> 00:04:09,598
that you could make and that your opponent could make.

128
00:04:09,599 --> 00:04:12,058
There is almost no hidden information in the game,

129
00:04:12,060 --> 00:04:13,830
which means that there's almost no luck.

130
00:04:13,830 --> 00:04:16,620
But poker and life are very different,

131
00:04:16,620 --> 00:04:18,780
in poker you can never be a 100% certain

132
00:04:18,779 --> 00:04:20,418
of the cards that your opponents are holding.

133
00:04:20,420 --> 00:04:23,160
And an only a couple of circumstances can you be confident

134
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:25,180
that you have the best hand at the table.

135
00:04:25,180 --> 00:04:27,329
In most cases, you're gonna have a losing hand.

136
00:04:27,329 --> 00:04:29,659
So, successful poker players have to, number one,

137
00:04:29,660 --> 00:04:30,910
become okay with the fact

138
00:04:30,910 --> 00:04:33,329
that they are going to lose more hands than they win.

139
00:04:33,329 --> 00:04:35,549
They have to work against the natural loss aversion

140
00:04:35,550 --> 00:04:37,270
that all humans experience,

141
00:04:37,269 --> 00:04:38,708
but they also have to become okay

142
00:04:38,709 --> 00:04:42,108
and comfortable working with incomplete information.

143
00:04:42,110 --> 00:04:44,380
They can do certain things to get more information,

144
00:04:44,379 --> 00:04:45,399
they can be very observant

145
00:04:45,399 --> 00:04:46,858
about the way their opponents bet,

146
00:04:46,860 --> 00:04:48,969
they can try to read tells and body language,

147
00:04:48,970 --> 00:04:50,720
but they're never gonna be 100% certain.

148
00:04:50,720 --> 00:04:52,990
And that is how we need to look at our decisions as well,

149
00:04:52,990 --> 00:04:55,490
because that's how pretty much the entire world works.

150
00:04:55,490 --> 00:04:57,077
Richard Feynman once said of science that,

151
00:04:57,076 --> 00:04:59,639
"Statements of science are not of what is true

152
00:04:59,639 --> 00:05:00,868
and what is not true,

153
00:05:00,870 --> 00:05:01,830
but statements of what is known

154
00:05:01,829 --> 00:05:03,849
to different degrees of certainty...

155
00:05:03,850 --> 00:05:05,309
every one of the concepts of science

156
00:05:05,310 --> 00:05:07,830
is on a scale graduated somewhere between,

157
00:05:07,829 --> 00:05:11,998
but at neither end of, absolute falsity or absolute truth."

158
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,129
And if we can become comfortable with that fact

159
00:05:14,129 --> 00:05:15,689
in our decision making process,

160
00:05:15,689 --> 00:05:17,979
and with the fact that the results of our decisions

161
00:05:17,980 --> 00:05:19,710
may not always be optimal

162
00:05:19,709 --> 00:05:22,099
even if our decision-making process was sound,

163
00:05:22,100 --> 00:05:23,630
then we're going to be more confident

164
00:05:23,629 --> 00:05:26,899
and more able to make decisions in the first place.

165
00:05:26,899 --> 00:05:28,548
So, now let's talk about the second problem

166
00:05:28,550 --> 00:05:29,880
we listed in the beginning of the video,

167
00:05:29,879 --> 00:05:31,669
the abundance of choice.

168
00:05:31,670 --> 00:05:33,280
Now, having a lot of choice

169
00:05:33,279 --> 00:05:35,059
seems like a good thing sometimes,

170
00:05:35,060 --> 00:05:36,770
but when you have too many choices,

171
00:05:36,769 --> 00:05:39,318
it can become a bad thing as anybody who's ever played

172
00:05:39,319 --> 00:05:42,059
with a Reliquary Tower and Magic Gathering knows.

173
00:05:42,060 --> 00:05:44,470
And that's because the more choice you have,

174
00:05:44,470 --> 00:05:46,530
the longer it often takes you to make a decision.

175
00:05:46,529 --> 00:05:48,168
In fact, there is a psychological principle

176
00:05:48,170 --> 00:05:50,010
called Hicks Law that describes this.

177
00:05:50,009 --> 00:05:52,999
As more and more stimuli are added to a pool of choices,

178
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:54,679
the longer and longer it takes the subject

179
00:05:54,680 --> 00:05:56,319
to actually make a choice.

180
00:05:56,319 --> 00:05:58,149
And this hesitation, isn't the only problem

181
00:05:58,149 --> 00:06:00,378
associated with the abundance of choice.

182
00:06:00,379 --> 00:06:02,689
As Sheena Iyengar wrote in one of her research papers

183
00:06:02,689 --> 00:06:05,355
on the paradox of choice and analysis paralysis,

184
00:06:05,357 --> 00:06:07,849
"The presence of more choices has been associated

185
00:06:07,850 --> 00:06:09,460
with lower chooser confidence

186
00:06:09,459 --> 00:06:11,869
and greater experiences of negative effect;

187
00:06:11,870 --> 00:06:15,010
that is, people choosing for more extensive choice sets

188
00:06:15,009 --> 00:06:17,908
are less satisfied with their decision outcomes

189
00:06:17,910 --> 00:06:22,160
and pay more for purchases that make them less happy."

190
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:23,760
She's also noted that the abundance of choice

191
00:06:23,759 --> 00:06:26,229
can often push people to never make a decision at all.

192
00:06:26,230 --> 00:06:28,1000
With her biggest example, being retirement savings options,

193
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,590
people are often so inundated

194
00:06:30,589 --> 00:06:32,409
with so many different investment choices

195
00:06:32,410 --> 00:06:34,280
that they never choose anything,

196
00:06:34,279 --> 00:06:35,809
and they never save for retirement.

197
00:06:35,810 --> 00:06:37,269
The worst possible decision,

198
00:06:37,269 --> 00:06:39,659
barring putting it all on black in Vegas or something.

199
00:06:39,660 --> 00:06:40,910
So, this abundance of choice

200
00:06:40,910 --> 00:06:42,549
that we often think is a good thing,

201
00:06:42,550 --> 00:06:44,199
can not only cause us to hesitate

202
00:06:44,199 --> 00:06:46,839
and put off important decisions, sometimes indefinitely.

203
00:06:46,839 --> 00:06:49,749
But it leads to us being less satisfied overall

204
00:06:49,750 --> 00:06:50,680
with our decisions,

205
00:06:50,680 --> 00:06:52,280
and it can cause us to spend more money

206
00:06:52,279 --> 00:06:54,399
on things that ultimately don't matter.

207
00:06:54,399 --> 00:06:56,089
And this leads to a conclusion,

208
00:06:56,089 --> 00:06:58,289
if you want to overthink less often,

209
00:06:58,290 --> 00:07:00,700
and if you want to be more satisfied with your decisions,

210
00:07:00,699 --> 00:07:04,058
you should restrict your choice pool, do it deliberately.

211
00:07:04,060 --> 00:07:06,180
For example, say you wanna buy a new TV.

212
00:07:06,180 --> 00:07:07,329
What do you do? Well,

213
00:07:07,329 --> 00:07:08,919
most people are probably gonna go on the internet

214
00:07:08,920 --> 00:07:10,420
and start reading TV reviews,

215
00:07:10,420 --> 00:07:13,540
but that exposes you to pretty much every TV you could buy,

216
00:07:13,540 --> 00:07:15,720
and it exposes you to hundreds, or thousands,

217
00:07:15,720 --> 00:07:18,289
or millions of different opinions, spec sheets,

218
00:07:18,290 --> 00:07:19,459
fact listings,

219
00:07:19,459 --> 00:07:22,238
and you could spend the rest of your life if you wanted to

220
00:07:22,240 --> 00:07:25,349
going through and comparing side-by-side all of these TVs

221
00:07:25,350 --> 00:07:26,390
with they're different specs.

222
00:07:26,389 --> 00:07:28,848
And maybe you're going to get the best overall TV

223
00:07:28,850 --> 00:07:30,160
at the end of the day if you do that.

224
00:07:30,160 --> 00:07:31,640
But again, the research shows

225
00:07:31,639 --> 00:07:33,399
we're gonna spend a lot of time hesitating,

226
00:07:33,399 --> 00:07:34,618
we're going to waste a lot of time

227
00:07:34,620 --> 00:07:36,620
comparing things that ultimately don't matter.

228
00:07:36,620 --> 00:07:39,300
And we're probably gonna convince ourselves to buy a TV

229
00:07:39,300 --> 00:07:41,400
that's more expensive than we really need.

230
00:07:41,399 --> 00:07:42,818
So, maybe what you should do instead

231
00:07:42,819 --> 00:07:46,198
is just walk into Target or your local electronics store

232
00:07:46,199 --> 00:07:48,889
and buy whatever TV looks good on the wall.

233
00:07:48,889 --> 00:07:50,048
Are you going to get the TV

234
00:07:50,050 --> 00:07:52,429
with the absolute best contrast ratio,

235
00:07:52,430 --> 00:07:54,659
and lag time, and all that kind of stuff?

236
00:07:54,660 --> 00:07:56,640
Probably not, but ask yourself this,

237
00:07:56,639 --> 00:07:58,848
six months down the line when you're watching a movie

238
00:07:58,850 --> 00:08:00,299
on your TV that you've had for a while,

239
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:01,220
it's up on the wall,

240
00:08:01,220 --> 00:08:03,149
you've gotten rid of the box and all that.

241
00:08:03,149 --> 00:08:05,718
Do you care about those features?

242
00:08:05,720 --> 00:08:09,139
'Cause personally I don't, the TV I have today is much,

243
00:08:09,139 --> 00:08:10,909
much better on a technological level

244
00:08:10,910 --> 00:08:12,250
than what I had when I was a kid

245
00:08:12,250 --> 00:08:13,689
watching TV at my grandma's house.

246
00:08:13,689 --> 00:08:16,088
But, if I really asked myself, honestly,

247
00:08:16,089 --> 00:08:19,189
I'm no happier watching TV on that big,

248
00:08:19,189 --> 00:08:21,309
fancy flat screen than I was watching TV

249
00:08:21,310 --> 00:08:23,990
on the gigantic furniture box my grandma had.

250
00:08:23,990 --> 00:08:26,559
The overall happiness level is really

251
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:27,870
the same at the end of the day.

252
00:08:27,870 --> 00:08:30,329
So, restricting my choice pool in this example

253
00:08:30,329 --> 00:08:31,659
would save me a lot of time,

254
00:08:31,660 --> 00:08:33,370
and probably save me a lot of money,

255
00:08:33,370 --> 00:08:35,939
and my overall satisfaction would be higher.

256
00:08:35,940 --> 00:08:36,870
Now, the third major problem

257
00:08:36,870 --> 00:08:38,059
that we talked about in the intro

258
00:08:38,059 --> 00:08:40,039
was the lack of prioritization.

259
00:08:40,039 --> 00:08:41,178
This can cause overthinking

260
00:08:41,179 --> 00:08:43,498
just as much as the abundance of choice, and fear,

261
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:45,020
in the decision-making process.

262
00:08:45,019 --> 00:08:46,839
How many times have you woken up with a task list

263
00:08:46,840 --> 00:08:48,440
that has five or 10 items on it,

264
00:08:48,440 --> 00:08:50,710
and you're not really sure of which one to start with.

265
00:08:50,710 --> 00:08:52,420
None of them have a hard deadline,

266
00:08:52,419 --> 00:08:54,878
so you spend a bunch of time procrastinating,

267
00:08:54,879 --> 00:08:57,408
just trying to figure out where you should start.

268
00:08:57,409 --> 00:08:59,578
That's a lack of priorities in action.

269
00:08:59,580 --> 00:09:00,413
And actually,

270
00:09:00,413 --> 00:09:02,980
the last example we just went through has an application

271
00:09:02,980 --> 00:09:04,409
of the tip that I'm gonna share with you,

272
00:09:04,409 --> 00:09:07,719
which is to go through what's called the regret exercise.

273
00:09:07,720 --> 00:09:10,260
This is a great way to set your priorities,

274
00:09:10,259 --> 00:09:13,089
even if they are not clear in the present moment.

275
00:09:13,090 --> 00:09:15,080
And this involves mentally fast forwarding

276
00:09:15,080 --> 00:09:16,070
to the end of the day,

277
00:09:16,070 --> 00:09:19,010
or the end of a specific time period and asking yourself,

278
00:09:19,009 --> 00:09:22,009
what choice would I regret the most here?

279
00:09:22,009 --> 00:09:23,609
So, in the case of having a to do list,

280
00:09:23,610 --> 00:09:24,980
if you've got 10 items on the list,

281
00:09:24,980 --> 00:09:26,740
mentally fast forward to the end of the day

282
00:09:26,740 --> 00:09:27,670
and ask yourself,

283
00:09:27,669 --> 00:09:31,269
which of these things would I regret most not getting done?

284
00:09:31,269 --> 00:09:32,259
And once you have your answer,

285
00:09:32,259 --> 00:09:34,379
you know what you should start working on right away.

286
00:09:34,379 --> 00:09:35,849
But the regret exercise works

287
00:09:35,850 --> 00:09:37,959
for longer time periods as well.

288
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:40,580
Personally, I always wanted to take vocal lessons,

289
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:42,180
but I was always really scared to do it.

290
00:09:42,179 --> 00:09:43,568
I was scared to embarrass myself,

291
00:09:43,570 --> 00:09:45,579
and I also had this little feeling in the back of my head.

292
00:09:45,580 --> 00:09:47,090
Like, I don't have a good voice,

293
00:09:47,090 --> 00:09:48,860
it's not even worth going to try to develop it

294
00:09:48,860 --> 00:09:51,139
because I'm not naturally a good singer.

295
00:09:51,139 --> 00:09:52,219
But then I asked myself, you know,

296
00:09:52,220 --> 00:09:55,260
I mentally fast-forwarded to myself at 80 years old

297
00:09:55,259 --> 00:09:58,518
and asked would I regret never taking vocal lessons?

298
00:09:58,519 --> 00:09:59,352
Never trying.

299
00:09:59,352 --> 00:10:01,019
And the answer was an absolute yes,

300
00:10:01,019 --> 00:10:02,458
is something that I wanted to do.

301
00:10:02,460 --> 00:10:05,520
And by mentally fast-forwarding out of my present moment,

302
00:10:05,519 --> 00:10:07,679
I was able to get clarity on that question,

303
00:10:07,679 --> 00:10:09,888
the answer to it was so much stronger.

304
00:10:09,889 --> 00:10:12,489
So, that pushed me to go and take my first lesson,

305
00:10:12,490 --> 00:10:14,690
and I'm really glad that I did.

306
00:10:14,690 --> 00:10:16,129
And going back to that TV example,

307
00:10:16,129 --> 00:10:18,559
I mentally fast forward it to a period six months

308
00:10:18,559 --> 00:10:20,989
after I bought the TV in my head and asked,

309
00:10:20,990 --> 00:10:23,219
do I really care about the contrast ratio?

310
00:10:23,220 --> 00:10:26,869
Do I really care if the TV is 70 inches or 65 inches?

311
00:10:26,870 --> 00:10:27,770
No, I don't.

312
00:10:27,769 --> 00:10:29,408
So, I should just go to Best Buy

313
00:10:29,409 --> 00:10:30,889
and buy whatever looks good.

314
00:10:30,889 --> 00:10:33,379
The regret exercise is very powerful

315
00:10:33,379 --> 00:10:35,038
and it's a great prioritization tool.

316
00:10:35,039 --> 00:10:35,872
Now, we have gone through

317
00:10:35,873 --> 00:10:37,969
some pretty powerful decision-making tools in this video,

318
00:10:37,970 --> 00:10:39,690
we talked about the experimental outlook,

319
00:10:39,690 --> 00:10:41,410
versus the set-path outlook.

320
00:10:41,409 --> 00:10:42,638
We talked about getting more comfortable

321
00:10:42,639 --> 00:10:44,688
with incomplete information like a poker player

322
00:10:44,690 --> 00:10:45,980
versus a chess player,

323
00:10:45,980 --> 00:10:47,369
we talked about the abundance of choice

324
00:10:47,370 --> 00:10:49,599
and purposely limiting your choice pools.

325
00:10:49,600 --> 00:10:50,433
You hesitate less

326
00:10:50,432 --> 00:10:52,448
and you're more satisfied with your decisions.

327
00:10:52,450 --> 00:10:53,740
And we also talked about getting more clear

328
00:10:53,740 --> 00:10:56,309
on your priorities utilizing the regret exercise.

329
